ab or window. Reload to refresh your session. Dismiss alert\n\n### Uh oh!\n\nThere was an error while loading. Please reload this page.\n\n[syntax-tree](/syntax-tree) / **[mdast](/syntax-tree/mdast)** Public\n\n-   ### Uh oh!\n    \n    There was an error while loading. Please reload this page.\n    \n-   [Notifications](/login?return_to=%2Fsyntax-tree%2Fmdast) You must be signed in to change notification settings\n-   [Fork 48](/login?return_to=%2Fsyntax-tree%2Fmdast)\n-   [Star 1.4k](/login?return_to=%2Fsyntax-tree%2Fmdast)\n    \n\n-   [Code](/syntax-tree/mdast)\n-   [Issues 0](/syntax-tree/mdast/issues)\n-   [Pull requests 0](/syntax-tree/mdast/pulls)\n-   [Actions](/syntax-tree/mdast/actions)\n-   [Security and quality 0](/syntax-tree/mdast/security)\n-   [Insights](/syntax-tree/mdast/pulse)\n\nAdditional navigation options\n\n-   [Code](/syntax-tree/mdast)\n-   [Issues](/syntax-tree/mdast/issues)\n-   [Pull requests](/syntax-tree/mdast/pulls)\n-   [Actions](/syntax-tree/mdast/actions)\n-   [Security and quality](/syntax-tree/mdast/security)\n-   [Insights](/syntax-tree/mdast/pulse)\n\n [](/syntax-tree/mdast)\n\n# syntax-tree/mdast\n\n main\n\n[Branches](/syntax-tree/mdast/branches)[Tags](/syntax-tree/mdast/tags)\n\n[](/syntax-tree/mdast/branches)[](/syntax-tree/mdast/tags)\n\nGo to file\n\nCode\n\nOpen more actions menu\n\n## Folders and files\n\nName\n\nName\n\nLast commit message\n\nLast commit date\n\n## Latest commit\n\n## History\n\n[119 Commits](/syntax-tree/mdast/commits/main/)\n\n[](/syntax-tree/mdast/commits/main/)119 Commits\n\n[.github/workflows](/syntax-tree/mdast/tree/main/.github/workflows \"This path skips through empty directories\")\n\n[.github/workflows](/syntax-tree/mdast/tree/main/.github/workflows \"This path skips through empty directories\")\n\n[.gitignore](/syntax-tree/mdast/blob/main/.gitignore \".gitignore\")\n\n[.gitignore](/syntax-tree/mdast/blob/main/.gitignore \".gitignore\")\n\n[.npmrc](/syntax-tree/mdast/blob/main/.npmrc \".npmrc\")\n\n[.npmrc](/syntax-tree/mdast/blob/main/.npmrc \".npmrc\")\n\n[logo.svg](/syntax-tree/mdast/blob/main/logo.svg \"logo.svg\")\n\n[logo.svg](/syntax-tree/mdast/blob/main/logo.svg \"logo.svg\")\n\n[package.json](/syntax-tree/mdast/blob/main/package.json \"package.json\")\n\n[package.json](/syntax-tree/mdast/blob/main/package.json \"package.json\")\n\n[readme.md](/syntax-tree/mdast/blob/main/readme.md \"readme.md\")\n\n[readme.md](/syntax-tree/mdast/blob/main/readme.md \"readme.md\")\n\nView all files\n\n## Repository files navigation\n\n-   [README](#)\n-   [Code of conduct](#)\n-   [Contributing](#)\n-   [Security](#)\n\nMore items\n\n# [![mdast](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/syntax-tree/mdast/e6b43aa/logo.svg?sanitize=true)](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/syntax-tree/mdast/e6b43aa/logo.svg?sanitize=true)\n\n[](#)\n\n**M**ark**d**own **A**bstract **S**yntax **T**ree.\n\n---\n\n**mdast** is a specification for representing markdown in a [syntax tree](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#syntax-tree). It implements **[unist](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist)**. It can represent several flavours of [markdown](https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/), such as [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org) and [GitHub Flavored Markdown](https://github.github.com/gfm/).\n\nThis document may not be released. See [releases](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast/releases) for released documents. The latest released version is [`5.0.0`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast/releases/tag/5.0.0).\n\n## Contents\n\n[](#contents)\n\n-   [Introduction](#introduction)\n    -   [Where this specification fits](#where-this-specification-fits)\n-   [Types](#types)\n-   [Nodes (abstract)](#nodes-abstract)\n    -   [`Literal`](#literal)\n    -   [`Parent`](#parent)\n-   [Nodes](#nodes)\n    -   [`Blockquote`](#blockquote)\n    -   [`Break`](#break)\n    -   [`Code`](#code)\n    -   [`Definition`](#definition)\n    -   [`Emphasis`](#emphasis)\n    -   [`Heading`](#heading)\n    -   [`Html`](#html)\n    -   [`Image`](#image)\n    -   [`ImageReference`](#imagereference)\n    -   [`InlineCode`](#inlinecode)\n    -   [`Link`](#link)\n    -   [`LinkReference`](#linkreference)\n    -   [`List`](#list)\n    -   [`ListItem`](#listitem)\n    -   [`Paragraph`](#paragraph)\n    -   [`Root`](#root)\n    -   [`Strong`](#strong)\n    -   [`Text`](#text)\n    -   [`ThematicBreak`](#thematicbreak)\n-   [Mixin](#mixin)\n    -   [`Alternative`](#alternative)\n    -   [`Association`](#association)\n    -   [`Reference`](#reference)\n    -   [`Resource`](#resource)\n-   [Enumeration](#enumeration)\n    -   [`referenceType`](#referencetype)\n-   [Content model](#content-model)\n    -   [`Content`](#content)\n    -   [`FlowContent`](#flowcontent)\n    -   [`ListContent`](#listcontent)\n    -   [`PhrasingContent`](#phrasingcontent)\n-   [Extensions](#extensions)\n    -   [GFM](#gfm)\n    -   [Frontmatter](#frontmatter)\n    -   [MDX](#mdx)\n-   [Glossary](#glossary)\n-   [List of utilities](#list-of-utilities)\n-   [References](#references)\n-   [Security](#security)\n-   [Related](#related)\n-   [Contribute](#contribute)\n-   [Acknowledgments](#acknowledgments)\n-   [License](#license)\n\n## Introduction\n\n[](#introduction)\n\nThis document defines a format for representing [markdown](https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/) as an [abstract syntax tree](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#syntax-tree). Development of mdast started in July 2014, in **[remark](https://github.com/remarkjs/remark)**, before [unist](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist) existed. This specification is written in a [Web IDL](https://heycam.github.io/webidl/)\\-like grammar.\n\n### Where this specification fits\n\n[](#where-this-specification-fits)\n\nmdast extends [unist](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist), a format for syntax trees, to benefit from its [ecosystem of utilities](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#list-of-utilities).\n\nmdast relates to [JavaScript](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/9.0/index.html) in that it has a rich [ecosystem of utilities](#list-of-utilities) for working with compliant syntax trees in JavaScript. However, mdast is not limited to JavaScript and can be used in other programming languages.\n\nmdast relates to the [unified](https://github.com/unifiedjs/unified) and [remark](https://github.com/remarkjs/remark) projects in that mdast syntax trees are used throughout their ecosystems.\n\n## Types\n\n[](#types)\n\nIf you are using TypeScript, you can use the unist types by installing them with npm:\n\nnpm install @types/mdast\n\n## Nodes (abstract)\n\n[](#nodes-abstract)\n\n### `Literal`\n\n[](#literal)\n\ninterface Literal <: UnistLiteral {\n  value: string\n}\n\n**Literal** ([**UnistLiteral**](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#literal)) represents an abstract interface in mdast containing a value.\n\nIts `value` field is a `string`.\n\n### `Parent`\n\n[](#parent)\n\ninterface Parent <: UnistParent {\n  children: \\[MdastContent\\]\n}\n\n**Parent** ([**UnistParent**](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#parent)) represents an abstract interface in mdast containing other nodes (said to be [*children*](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#child)).\n\nIts content is limited to only other [**mdast content**](#content-model).\n\n## Nodes\n\n[](#nodes)\n\n### `Blockquote`\n\n[](#blockquote)\n\ninterface Blockquote <: Parent {\n  type: 'blockquote'\n  children: \\[FlowContent\\]\n}\n\n**Blockquote** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents a section quoted from somewhere else.\n\n**Blockquote** can be used where [**flow**](#flowcontent) content is expected. Its content model is also [**flow**](#flowcontent) content.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\> Alpha bravo charlie.\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'blockquote',\n  children: \\[{\n    type: 'paragraph',\n    children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'Alpha bravo charlie.'}\\]\n  }\\]\n}\n\n### `Break`\n\n[](#break)\n\ninterface Break <: Node {\n  type: 'break'\n}\n\n**Break** ([**Node**](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#node)) represents a line break, such as in poems or addresses.\n\n**Break** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. It has no content model.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\nfoo··\nbar\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'paragraph',\n  children: \\[\n    {type: 'text', value: 'foo'},\n    {type: 'break'},\n    {type: 'text', value: 'bar'}\n  \\]\n}\n\n### `Code`\n\n[](#code)\n\ninterface Code <: Literal {\n  type: 'code'\n  lang: string?\n  meta: string?\n}\n\n**Code** ([**Literal**](#literal)) represents a block of preformatted text, such as ASCII art or computer code.\n\n**Code** can be used where [**flow**](#flowcontent) content is expected. Its content is represented by its `value` field.\n\nThis node relates to the [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content concept [**InlineCode**](#inlinecode).\n\nA `lang` field can be present. It represents the language of computer code being marked up.\n\nIf the `lang` field is present, a `meta` field can be present. It represents custom information relating to the node.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n    foo()\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'code',\n  lang: null,\n  meta: null,\n  value: 'foo()'\n}\n\nAnd the following markdown:\n\n\\`\\`\\`js highlight-line=\"2\"\nfoo()\nbar()\nbaz()\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'code',\n  lang: 'js',\n  meta: 'highlight-line=\"2\"',\n  value: 'foo()\\\\nbar()\\\\nbaz()'\n}\n\n### `Definition`\n\n[](#definition)\n\ninterface Definition <: Node {\n  type: 'definition'\n}\n\nDefinition includes Association\nDefinition includes Resource\n\n**Definition** ([**Node**](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#node)) represents a resource.\n\n**Definition** can be used where [**content**](#content) is expected. It has no content model.\n\n**Definition** includes the mixins [**Association**](#association) and [**Resource**](#resource).\n\n**Definition** should be associated with [**LinkReferences**](#linkreference) and [**ImageReferences**](#imagereference).\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\[Alpha\\]: https://example.com\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'definition',\n  identifier: 'alpha',\n  label: 'Alpha',\n  url: 'https://example.com',\n  title: null\n}\n\n### `Emphasis`\n\n[](#emphasis)\n\ninterface Emphasis <: Parent {\n  type: 'emphasis'\n  children: \\[PhrasingContent\\]\n}\n\n**Emphasis** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents stress emphasis of its contents.\n\n**Emphasis** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. Its content model is [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\*alpha\\* \\_bravo\\_\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'paragraph',\n  children: \\[\n    {\n      type: 'emphasis',\n      children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'alpha'}\\]\n    },\n    {type: 'text', value: ' '},\n    {\n      type: 'emphasis',\n      children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'bravo'}\\]\n    }\n  \\]\n}\n\n### `Heading`\n\n[](#heading)\n\ninterface Heading <: Parent {\n  type: 'heading'\n  depth: 1 <\\= number <\\= 6\n  children: \\[PhrasingContent\\]\n}\n\n**Heading** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents a heading of a section.\n\n**Heading** can be used where [**flow**](#flowcontent) content is expected. Its content model is [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content.\n\nA `depth` field must be present. A value of `1` is said to be the highest rank and `6` the lowest.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\# Alpha\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'heading',\n  depth: 1,\n  children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'Alpha'}\\]\n}\n\n### `Html`\n\n[](#html)\n\ninterface Html <: Literal {\n  type: 'html'\n}\n\n**Html** ([**Literal**](#literal)) represents a fragment of raw [HTML](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/).\n\n**Html** can be used where [**flow**](#flowcontent) or [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. Its content is represented by its `value` field.\n\n**Html** nodes do not have the restriction of being valid or complete HTML ([\\[HTML\\]](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/)) constructs.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n<div\\>\n\nYields:\n\n{type: 'html', value: '<div>'}\n\n### `Image`\n\n[](#image)\n\ninterface Image <: Node {\n  type: 'image'\n}\n\nImage includes Resource\nImage includes Alternative\n\n**Image** ([**Node**](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#node)) represents an image.\n\n**Image** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. It has no content model, but is described by its `alt` field.\n\n**Image** includes the mixins [**Resource**](#resource) and [**Alternative**](#alternative).\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n!\\[alpha\\](https://example.com/favicon.ico \"bravo\")\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'image',\n  url: 'https://example.com/favicon.ico',\n  title: 'bravo',\n  alt: 'alpha'\n}\n\n### `ImageReference`\n\n[](#imagereference)\n\ninterface ImageReference <: Node {\n  type: 'imageReference'\n}\n\nImageReference includes Reference\nImageReference includes Alternative\n\n**ImageReference** ([**Node**](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#node)) represents an image through association, or its original source if there is no association.\n\n**ImageReference** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. It has no content model, but is described by its `alt` field.\n\n**ImageReference** includes the mixins [**Reference**](#reference) and [**Alternative**](#alternative).\n\n**ImageReference** should be associated with a [**Definition**](#definition).\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n!\\[alpha\\]\\[bravo\\]\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'imageReference',\n  identifier: 'bravo',\n  label: 'bravo',\n  referenceType: 'full',\n  alt: 'alpha'\n}\n\n### `InlineCode`\n\n[](#inlinecode)\n\ninterface InlineCode <: Literal {\n  type: 'inlineCode'\n}\n\n**InlineCode** ([**Literal**](#literal)) represents a fragment of computer code, such as a file name, computer program, or anything a computer could parse.\n\n**InlineCode** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. Its content is represented by its `value` field.\n\nThis node relates to the [**flow**](#flowcontent) content concept [**Code**](#code).\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\`foo()\\`\n\nYields:\n\n{type: 'inlineCode', value: 'foo()'}\n\n### `Link`\n\n[](#link)\n\ninterface Link <: Parent {\n  type: 'link'\n  children: \\[PhrasingContent\\]\n}\n\nLink includes Resource\n\n**Link** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents a hyperlink.\n\n**Link** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. Its content model is also [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content.\n\n**Link** includes the mixin [**Resource**](#resource).\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\[alpha\\](https://example.com \"bravo\")\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'link',\n  url: 'https://example.com',\n  title: 'bravo',\n  children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'alpha'}\\]\n}\n\n### `LinkReference`\n\n[](#linkreference)\n\ninterface LinkReference <: Parent {\n  type: 'linkReference'\n  children: \\[PhrasingContent\\]\n}\n\nLinkReference includes Reference\n\n**LinkReference** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents a hyperlink through association, or its original source if there is no association.\n\n**LinkReference** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. Its content model is also [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content.\n\n**LinkReference** includes the mixin [**Reference**](#reference).\n\n**LinkReferences** should be associated with a [**Definition**](#definition).\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\[alpha\\]\\[Bravo\\]\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'linkReference',\n  identifier: 'bravo',\n  label: 'Bravo',\n  referenceType: 'full',\n  children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'alpha'}\\]\n}\n\n### `List`\n\n[](#list)\n\ninterface List <: Parent {\n  type: 'list'\n  ordered: boolean?\n  start: number?\n  spread: boolean?\n  children: \\[ListContent\\]\n}\n\n**List** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents a list of items.\n\n**List** can be used where [**flow**](#flowcontent) content is expected. Its content model is [**list**](#listcontent) content.\n\nAn `ordered` field can be present. It represents that the items have been intentionally ordered (when `true`), or that the order of items is not important (when `false` or not present).\n\nA `start` field can be present. It represents, when the `ordered` field is `true`, the starting number of the list.\n\nA `spread` field can be present. It represents that one or more of its children are separated with a blank line from its [siblings](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#sibling) (when `true`), or not (when `false` or not present).\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n1. foo\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'list',\n  ordered: true,\n  start: 1,\n  spread: false,\n  children: \\[{\n    type: 'listItem',\n    spread: false,\n    children: \\[{\n      type: 'paragraph',\n      children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'foo'}\\]\n    }\\]\n  }\\]\n}\n\n### `ListItem`\n\n[](#listitem)\n\ninterface ListItem <: Parent {\n  type: 'listItem'\n  spread: boolean?\n  children: \\[FlowContent\\]\n}\n\n**ListItem** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents an item in a [**List**](#list).\n\n**ListItem** can be used where [**list**](#listcontent) content is expected. Its content model is [**flow**](#flowcontent) content.\n\nA `spread` field can be present. It represents that the item contains two or more [*children*](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#child) separated by a blank line (when `true`), or not (when `false` or not present).\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\* bar\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'listItem',\n  spread: false,\n  children: \\[{\n    type: 'paragraph',\n    children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'bar'}\\]\n  }\\]\n}\n\n### `Paragraph`\n\n[](#paragraph)\n\ninterface Paragraph <: Parent {\n  type: 'paragraph'\n  children: \\[PhrasingContent\\]\n}\n\n**Paragraph** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents a unit of discourse dealing with a particular point or idea.\n\n**Paragraph** can be used where [**content**](#content) is expected. Its content model is [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\nAlpha bravo charlie.\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'paragraph',\n  children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'Alpha bravo charlie.'}\\]\n}\n\n### `Root`\n\n[](#root)\n\ninterface Root <: Parent {\n  type: 'root'\n}\n\n**Root** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents a document.\n\n**Root** can be used as the [*root*](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#root) of a [*tree*](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#tree), never as a [*child*](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#child). Its content model is **not** limited to [**flow**](#flowcontent) content, but instead can contain any [**mdast content**](#content-model) with the restriction that all content must be of the same category.\n\n### `Strong`\n\n[](#strong)\n\ninterface Strong <: Parent {\n  type: 'strong'\n  children: \\[PhrasingContent\\]\n}\n\n**Strong** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents strong importance, seriousness, or urgency for its contents.\n\n**Strong** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. Its content model is [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\*\\*alpha\\*\\* \\_\\_bravo\\_\\_\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'paragraph',\n  children: \\[\n    {\n      type: 'strong',\n      children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'alpha'}\\]\n    },\n    {type: 'text', value: ' '},\n    {\n      type: 'strong',\n      children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'bravo'}\\]\n    }\n  \\]\n}\n\n### `Text`\n\n[](#text)\n\ninterface Text <: Literal {\n  type: 'text'\n}\n\n**Text** ([**Literal**](#literal)) represents everything that is just text.\n\n**Text** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. Its content is represented by its `value` field.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\nAlpha bravo charlie.\n\nYields:\n\n{type: 'text', value: 'Alpha bravo charlie.'}\n\n### `ThematicBreak`\n\n[](#thematicbreak)\n\ninterface ThematicBreak <: Node {\n  type: 'thematicBreak'\n}\n\n**ThematicBreak** ([**Node**](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#node)) represents a thematic break, such as a scene change in a story, a transition to another topic, or a new document.\n\n**ThematicBreak** can be used where [**flow**](#flowcontent) content is expected. It has no content model.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nYields:\n\n{type: 'thematicBreak'}\n\n## Mixin\n\n[](#mixin)\n\n### `Alternative`\n\n[](#alternative)\n\ninterface mixin Alternative {\n  alt: string?\n}\n\n**Alternative** represents a node with a fallback\n\nAn `alt` field should be present. It represents equivalent content for environments that cannot represent the node as intended.\n\n### `Association`\n\n[](#association)\n\ninterface mixin Association {\n  identifier: string\n  label: string?\n}\n\n**Association** represents an internal relation from one node to another.\n\nAn `identifier` field must be present. It can match another node. `identifier` is a source value: character escapes and character references are *not* parsed. Its value must be normalized.\n\nA `label` field can be present. `label` is a string value: it works just like `title` on a link or a `lang` on code: character escapes and character references are parsed.\n\nTo normalize a value, collapse markdown whitespace (`[\\t\\n\\r ]+`) to a space, trim the optional initial and/or final space, and perform case-folding.\n\nWhether the value of `identifier` (or normalized `label` if there is no `identifier`) is expected to be a unique identifier or not depends on the type of node including the **Association**. An example of this is that they should be unique on [**Definition**](#definition), whereas multiple [**LinkReference**](#linkreference)s can be non-unique to be associated with one definition.\n\n### `Reference`\n\n[](#reference)\n\ninterface mixin Reference {\n  referenceType: string\n}\n\nReference includes Association\n\n**Reference** represents a marker that is [**associated**](#association) to another node.\n\nA `referenceType` field must be present. Its value must be a [**referenceType**](#referencetype). It represents the explicitness of the reference.\n\n### `Resource`\n\n[](#resource)\n\ninterface mixin Resource {\n  url: string\n  title: string?\n}\n\n**Resource** represents a reference to resource.\n\nA `url` field must be present. It represents a URL to the referenced resource.\n\nA `title` field can be present. It represents advisory information for the resource, such as would be appropriate for a tooltip.\n\n## Enumeration\n\n[](#enumeration)\n\n### `referenceType`\n\n[](#referencetype)\n\nenum referenceType {\n  'shortcut' | 'collapsed' | 'full'\n}\n\n**referenceType** represents the explicitness of a reference.\n\n-   **shortcut**: the reference is implicit, its identifier inferred from its content\n-   **collapsed**: the reference is explicit, its identifier inferred from its content\n-   **full**: the reference is explicit, its identifier explicitly set\n\n## Content model\n\n[](#content-model)\n\ntype MdastContent = FlowContent | ListContent | PhrasingContent\n\nEach node in mdast falls into one or more categories of **Content** that group nodes with similar characteristics together.\n\n### `Content`\n\n[](#content)\n\ntype Content = Definition | Paragraph\n\n**Content** represents runs of text that form definitions and paragraphs.\n\n### `FlowContent`\n\n[](#flowcontent)\n\ntype FlowContent =\n  Blockquote | Code | Heading | Html | List | ThematicBreak | Content\n\n**Flow** content represent the sections of document.\n\n### `ListContent`\n\n[](#listcontent)\n\ntype ListContent = ListItem\n\n**List** content represent the items in a list.\n\n### `PhrasingContent`\n\n[](#phrasingcontent)\n\ntype PhrasingContent = Break | Emphasis | Html | Image | ImageReference\n  | InlineCode | Link | LinkReference | Strong | Text\n\n**Phrasing** content represent the text in a document and its markup.\n\n## Extensions\n\n[](#extensions)\n\nMarkdown syntax is often extended. It is not a goal of this specification to list all possible extensions. However, a short list of frequently used extensions are shown below.\n\n### GFM\n\n[](#gfm)\n\nThe following interfaces are found in [GitHub Flavored Markdown](https://github.github.com/gfm/).\n\n#### `Delete`\n\n[](#delete)\n\ninterface Delete <: Parent {\n  type: 'delete'\n  children: \\[PhrasingContent\\]\n}\n\n**Delete** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents contents that are no longer accurate or no longer relevant.\n\n**Delete** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. Its content model is [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n~~alpha~~\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'delete',\n  children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'alpha'}\\]\n}\n\n#### `ListItem` (GFM)\n\n[](#listitem-gfm)\n\ninterface ListItemGfm <: ListItem {\n  checked: boolean?\n}\n\nIn GFM, a `checked` field can be present. It represents whether the item is done (when `true`), not done (when `false`), or indeterminate or not applicable (when `null` or not present).\n\n#### `FootnoteDefinition`\n\n[](#footnotedefinition)\n\ninterface FootnoteDefinition <: Parent {\n  type: 'footnoteDefinition'\n  children: \\[FlowContent\\]\n}\n\nFootnoteDefinition includes Association\n\n**FootnoteDefinition** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents content relating to the document that is outside its flow.\n\n**FootnoteDefinition** can be used where [**flow**](#flowcontent) content is expected. Its content model is also [**flow**](#flowcontent) content.\n\n**FootnoteDefinition** includes the mixin [**Association**](#association).\n\n**FootnoteDefinition** should be associated with [**FootnoteReferences**](#footnotereference).\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\[^alpha\\]: bravo and charlie.\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'footnoteDefinition',\n  identifier: 'alpha',\n  label: 'alpha',\n  children: \\[{\n    type: 'paragraph',\n    children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'bravo and charlie.'}\\]\n  }\\]\n}\n\n#### `FootnoteReference`\n\n[](#footnotereference)\n\ninterface FootnoteReference <: Node {\n  type: 'footnoteReference'\n}\n\nFootnoteReference includes Association\n\n**FootnoteReference** ([**Node**](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#node)) represents a marker through association.\n\n**FootnoteReference** can be used where [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content is expected. It has no content model.\n\n**FootnoteReference** includes the mixin [**Association**](#association).\n\n**FootnoteReference** should be associated with a [**FootnoteDefinition**](#footnotedefinition).\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\[^alpha\\]\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'footnoteReference',\n  identifier: 'alpha',\n  label: 'alpha'\n}\n\n#### `Table`\n\n[](#table)\n\ninterface Table <: Parent {\n  type: 'table'\n  align: \\[alignType\\]?\n  children: \\[TableContent\\]\n}\n\n**Table** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents two-dimensional data.\n\n**Table** can be used where [**flow**](#flowcontent) content is expected. Its content model is [**table**](#tablecontent) content.\n\nThe [*head*](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#head) of the node represents the labels of the columns.\n\nAn `align` field can be present. If present, it must be a list of [**alignType**s](#aligntype). It represents how cells in columns are aligned.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n| foo | bar |\n| :-- | :-: |\n| baz | qux |\n\nYields:\n\n{\n  type: 'table',\n  align: \\['left', 'center'\\],\n  children: \\[\n    {\n      type: 'tableRow',\n      children: \\[\n        {\n          type: 'tableCell',\n          children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'foo'}\\]\n        },\n        {\n          type: 'tableCell',\n          children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'bar'}\\]\n        }\n      \\]\n    },\n    {\n      type: 'tableRow',\n      children: \\[\n        {\n          type: 'tableCell',\n          children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'baz'}\\]\n        },\n        {\n          type: 'tableCell',\n          children: \\[{type: 'text', value: 'qux'}\\]\n        }\n      \\]\n    }\n  \\]\n}\n\n#### `TableCell`\n\n[](#tablecell)\n\ninterface TableCell <: Parent {\n  type: 'tableCell'\n  children: \\[PhrasingContent\\]\n}\n\n**TableCell** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents a header cell in a [**Table**](#table), if its parent is a [*head*](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#head), or a data cell otherwise.\n\n**TableCell** can be used where [**row**](#rowcontent) content is expected. Its content model is [**phrasing**](#phrasingcontent) content excluding [**Break**](#break) nodes.\n\nFor an example, see [**Table**](#table).\n\n#### `TableRow`\n\n[](#tablerow)\n\ninterface TableRow <: Parent {\n  type: 'tableRow'\n  children: \\[RowContent\\]\n}\n\n**TableRow** ([**Parent**](#parent)) represents a row of cells in a table.\n\n**TableRow** can be used where [**table**](#tablecontent) content is expected. Its content model is [**row**](#rowcontent) content.\n\nIf the node is a [*head*](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#head), it represents the labels of the columns for its parent [**Table**](#table).\n\nFor an example, see [**Table**](#table).\n\n#### `alignType`\n\n[](#aligntype)\n\nenum alignType {\n  'left' | 'right' | 'center' | null\n}\n\n**alignType** represents how phrasing content is aligned ([\\[CSSTEXT\\]](https://drafts.csswg.org/css-text/)).\n\n-   **`'left'`**: See the [`left`](https://drafts.csswg.org/css-text/#valdef-text-align-left) value of the `text-align` CSS property\n-   **`'right'`**: See the [`right`](https://drafts.csswg.org/css-text/#valdef-text-align-right) value of the `text-align` CSS property\n-   **`'center'`**: See the [`center`](https://drafts.csswg.org/css-text/#valdef-text-align-center) value of the `text-align` CSS property\n-   **`null`**: phrasing content is aligned as defined by the host environment\n\n#### `FlowContent` (GFM)\n\n[](#flowcontent-gfm)\n\ntype FlowContentGfm = FootnoteDefinition | Table | FlowContent\n\n#### `ListContent` (GFM)\n\n[](#listcontent-gfm)\n\ntype ListContentGfm = ListItemGfm\n\n#### `PhrasingContent` (GFM)\n\n[](#phrasingcontent-gfm)\n\ntype PhrasingContentGfm = FootnoteReference | Delete | PhrasingContent\n\n#### `RowContent`\n\n[](#rowcontent)\n\ntype RowContent = TableCell\n\n**Row** content represent the cells in a row.\n\n#### `TableContent`\n\n[](#tablecontent)\n\ntype TableContent = TableRow\n\n**Table** content represent the rows in a table.\n\n### Frontmatter\n\n[](#frontmatter)\n\nThe following interfaces are found with YAML.\n\n#### `Yaml`\n\n[](#yaml)\n\ninterface Yaml <: Literal {\n  type: 'yaml'\n}\n\n**Yaml** ([**Literal**](#literal)) represents a collection of metadata for the document in the YAML ([\\[YAML\\]](https://yaml.org)) data serialisation language.\n\n**Yaml** can be used where [**frontmatter**](#frontmattercontent) content is expected. Its content is represented by its `value` field.\n\nFor example, the following markdown:\n\n\\---\nfoo: bar\n\\---\n\nYields:\n\n{type: 'yaml', value: 'foo: bar'}\n\n#### `FrontmatterContent`\n\n[](#frontmattercontent)\n\ntype FrontmatterContent = Yaml\n\n**Frontmatter** content represent out-of-band information about the document.\n\nIf frontmatter is present, it must be limited to one node in the [*tree*](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#tree), and can only exist as a [*head*](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#head).\n\n#### `FlowContent` (frontmatter)\n\n[](#flowcontent-frontmatter)\n\ntype FlowContentFrontmatter = FrontmatterContent | FlowContent\n\n### MDX\n\n[](#mdx)\n\nSee [`remark-mdx`](https://mdxjs.com/packages/remark-mdx/#syntax-tree).\n\n## Glossary\n\n[](#glossary)\n\nSee the [unist glossary](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#glossary).\n\n## List of utilities\n\n[](#list-of-utilities)\n\nSee the [unist list of utilities](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist#list-of-utilities) for more utilities.\n\n-   [`mdast-add-list-metadata`](https://gitlab.com/staltz/mdast-add-list-metadata) — enhance the metadata of `list` and `listItem` nodes\n-   [`mdast-util-assert`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-assert) — assert nodes\n-   [`mdast-builder`](https://github.com/mike-north/mdast-builder) — build mdast structures with composable functions\n-   [`mdast-comment-marker`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-comment-marker) — parse a comment marker\n-   [`mdast-util-compact`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-compact) — make a tree compact\n-   [`mdast-util-definitions`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-definitions) — find definition nodes\n-   [`mdast-util-directive`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-directive) — parse and serialize directives\n-   [`mdast-util-find-and-replace`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-find-and-replace) — find and replace text\n-   [`mdast-flatten-image-paragraphs`](https://gitlab.com/staltz/mdast-flatten-image-paragraphs) — flatten `paragraph` and `image` into one `image` node\n-   [`mdast-flatten-listitem-paragraphs`](https://gitlab.com/staltz/mdast-flatten-listitem-paragraphs) — flatten `listItem` and (nested) paragraph into one listItem node\n-   [`mdast-flatten-nested-lists`](https://gitlab.com/staltz/mdast-flatten-nested-lists) — transform a tree to avoid lists in lists\n-   [`mdast-util-from-adf`](https://github.com/bitcrowd/mdast-util-from-adf) — build mdast syntax tree from Atlassian Document Format (ADF)\n-   [`mdast-util-from-markdown`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-from-markdown) — parse markdown\n-   [`mdast-util-frontmatter`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-frontmatter) — parse and serialize frontmatter\n-   [`mdast-util-gfm`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-gfm) — parse and serialize GFM\n-   [`mdast-util-gfm-autolink-literal`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-gfm-autolink-literal) — parse and serialize GFM autolink literals\n-   [`mdast-util-gfm-footnote`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-gfm-footnote) — parse and serialize GFM footnotes\n-   [`mdast-util-gfm-strikethrough`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-gfm-strikethrough) — parse and serialize GFM strikethrough\n-   [`mdast-util-gfm-table`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-gfm-table) — parse and serialize GFM tables\n-   [`mdast-util-gfm-task-list-item`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-gfm-task-list-item) — parse and serialize GFM task list items\n-   [`mdast-util-gridtables`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-gridtables) — parse and serialize gridtables\n-   [`mdast-util-heading-range`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-heading-range) — markdown heading as ranges\n-   [`mdast-util-heading-style`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-heading-style) — get the style of a heading node\n-   [`mdast-util-hidden`](https://github.com/Xunnamius/unified-utils/tree/main/packages/mdast-util-hidden) — prevent nodes from being seen by transformers.\n-   [`mdast-util-math`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-math) — parse and serialize math\n-   [`mdast-util-mdx`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-mdx) — parse and serialize MDX\n-   [`mdast-util-mdx-expression`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-mdx-expression) — parse and serialize MDX expressions\n-   [`mdast-util-mdx-jsx`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-mdx-jsx) — parse and serialize MDX JSX\n-   [`mdast-util-mdxjs-esm`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-mdxjs-esm) — parse and serialize MDX ESM\n-   [`mdast-move-images-to-root`](https://gitlab.com/staltz/mdast-move-images-to-root) — move image nodes up the tree until they are direct children of the root\n-   [`mdast-normalize-headings`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-normalize-headings) — ensure at most one top-level heading is in the document\n-   [`mdast-util-phrasing`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-phrasing) — check if a node is phrasing content\n-   [`mdast-squeeze-paragraphs`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-squeeze-paragraphs) — remove empty paragraphs\n-   [`mdast-util-toc`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-toc) — generate a table of contents from a tree\n-   [`mdast-util-to-hast`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-to-hast) — transform to hast\n-   [`mdast-util-to-markdown`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-to-markdown) — serialize markdown\n-   [`mdast-util-to-nlcst`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-to-nlcst) — transform to nlcst\n-   [`mdast-util-to-string`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-util-to-string) — get the plain text content of a node\n-   [`mdast-zone`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/mdast-zone) — HTML comments as ranges or markers\n\n## References\n\n[](#references)\n\n-   **unist**: [Universal Syntax Tree](https://github.com/syntax-tree/unist). T. Wormer; et al.\n-   **Markdown**: [Markdown](https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/). J. Gruber.\n-   **CommonMark**: [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org). J. MacFarlane; et al.\n-   **GFM**: [GitHub Flavored Markdown](https://github.github.com/gfm/). GitHub.\n-   **HTML**: [HTML Standard](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/), A. van Kesteren; et al. WHATWG.\n-   **CSSTEXT**: [CSS Text](https://drafts.csswg.org/css-text/), CSS Text, E. Etemad, K. Ishii. W3C.\n-   **JavaScript**: [ECMAScript Language Specification](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/9.0/index.html). Ecma International.\n-   **YAML**: [YAML Ain’t Markup Language](https://yaml.org), O. Ben-Kiki, C. Evans, I. döt Net.\n-   **Web IDL**: [Web IDL](https://heycam.github.io/webidl/), C. McCormack. W3C.\n\n## Security\n\n[](#security)\n\nAs mdast can contain HTML and be used to represent HTML, and improper use of HTML can open you up to a [cross-site scripting (XSS)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross-site_scripting) attack, improper use of mdast is also unsafe. When transforming to HTML (typically through [**hast**](https://github.com/syntax-tree/hast)), always be careful with user input and use [`hast-util-santize`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/hast-util-sanitize) to make the hast tree safe.\n\n## Related\n\n[](#related)\n\n-   [hast](https://github.com/syntax-tree/hast) — Hypertext Abstract Syntax Tree format\n-   [nlcst](https://github.com/syntax-tree/nlcst) — Natural Language Concrete Syntax Tree format\n-   [xast](https://github.com/syntax-tree/xast) — Extensible Abstract Syntax Tree\n\n## Contribute\n\n[](#contribute)\n\nSee [`contributing.md`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/.github/blob/HEAD/contributing.md) in [`syntax-tree/.github`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/.github) for ways to get started. See [`support.md`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/.github/blob/HEAD/support.md) for ways to get help. Ideas for new utilities and tools can be posted in [`syntax-tree/ideas`](https://github.com/syntax-tree/ideas).\n\nA curated list of awesome `syntax-tree`, unist, mdast, hast, xast, and nlcst resources, can be found in [awesome syntax-tree](https://github.com/syntax-tree/awesome-syntax-tree).\n\nThis project has a [code of conduct](https://github.com/syntax-tree/.github/blob/HEAD/code-of-conduct.md). By interacting with this repository, organization, or community you agree to abide by its terms.\n\n## Acknowledgments\n\n[](#acknowledgments)\n\nThe initial release of this project was authored by [**@wooorm**](https://github.com/wooorm).\n\nSpecial thanks to [**@eush77**](https://github.com/eush77) for their work, ideas, and incredibly valuable feedback!\n\nThanks to [**@anandthakker**](https://github.com/anandthakker), [**@arobase-che**](https://github.com/arobase-che), [**@BarryThePenguin**](https://github.com/BarryThePenguin), [**@chinesedfan**](https://github.com/chinesedfan), [**@ChristianMurphy**](https://github.com/ChristianMurphy), [**@craftzdog**](https://github.com/craftzdog), [**@d4rekanguok**](https://github.com/d4rekanguok), [**@detj**](https://github.com/detj), [**@dominictarr**](https://github.com/dominictarr), [**@gkatsev**](https://github.com/gkatsev), [**@Hamms**](https://github.com/Hamms), [**@Hypercubed**](https://github.com/Hypercubed), [**@ikatyang**](https://github.com/ikatyang), [**@izumin5210**](https://github.com/izumin5210), [**@jasonLaster**](https://github.com/jasonLaster), [**@Justineo**](https://github.com/Justineo), [**@justjake**](https://github.com/justjake), [**@KyleAMathews**](https://github.com/KyleAMathews), [**@laysent**](https://github.com/laysent), [**@macklinu**](https://github.com/macklinu), [**@mike-north**](https://github.com/mike-north), [**@Murderlon**](https://github.com/Murderlon), [**@nevik**](https://github.com/nevik), [**@Rokt33r**](https://github.com/Rokt33r), [**@rhysd**](https://github.com/rhysd), [**@rubys**](https://github.com/rubys), [**@Sarah-Seo**](https://github.com/Sarah-Seo), [**@sethvincent**](https://github.com/sethvincent), [**@silvenon**](https://github.com/silvenon), [**@simov**](https://github.com/simov), [**@staltz**](https://github.com/staltz), [**@stefanprobst**](https://github.com/stefanprobst), [**@tmcw**](https://github.com/tmcw), and [**@vhf**](https://github.com/vhf) for contributing to mdast and related projects!\n\n## License\n\n[](#license)\n\n[CC-BY-4.0](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/) © [Titus Wormer](https://wooorm.com)\n\n## About\n\nMarkdown Abstract Syntax Tree format\n\n[unifiedjs.com](https://unifiedjs.com \"https://unifiedjs.com\")\n\n### Topics\n\n[markdown](/topics/markdown \"Topic: markdown\") [ast](/topics/ast \"Topic: ast\") [syntax-tree](/topics/syntax-tree \"Topic: syntax-tree\") [unist](/topics/unist \"Topic: unist\")\n\n### Resources\n\n[Readme](#readme-ov-file)\n\n### Code of conduct\n\n[Code of conduct](#coc-ov-file)\n\n### Contributing\n\n[Contributing](#contributing-ov-file)\n\n### Security policy\n\n[Security policy](#security-ov-file)\n\n### Uh oh!\n\nThere was an error while loading. Please reload this page.\n\n[Activity](/syntax-tree/mdast/activity)\n\n[Custom properties](/syntax-tree/mdast/custom-properties)\n\n### Stars\n\n**1.4k** stars\n\n### Watchers\n\n**17** watching\n\n### Forks\n\n[**48** forks](/syntax-tree/mdast/forks)\n\n[Report repository](/contact/report-content?content_url=https%3A%2F%2Fgithub.com%2Fsyntax-tree%2Fmdast&report=syntax-tree+%28user%29)\n\n## [Releases 7](/syntax-tree/mdast/releases)\n\n[\n\n5.0.0 Latest\n\nJun 28, 2023\n\n\n\n](/syntax-tree/mdast/releases/tag/5.0.0)\n\n[\\+ 6 releases](/syntax-tree/mdast/releases)\n\n## Sponsor this project\n\n ### Uh oh!\n\nThere was an error while loading. Please reload this page.\n\n-    ![open_collective](https://github.githubassets.com/assets/open_collective-0a706523753d.svg)[opencollective.com/**unified**](https://opencollective.com/unified)\n-    ![thanks_dev](https://github.githubassets.com/assets/thanks_dev-0fe87803d1ed.svg)[thanks.dev/**u/gh/syntax-tree**](https://thanks.dev/u/gh/syntax-tree)\n\n[Learn more about GitHub Sponsors](/sponsors)\n\n### Uh oh!\n\nThere was an error while loading. Please reload this page.\n\n## [Contributors](/syntax-tree/mdast/graphs/contributors)\n\n### Uh oh!\n\nThere was an error while loading. Please reload this page.\n\n## Footer\n\n[](https://github.com)© 2026 GitHub, Inc.\n\n### Footer navigation\n\n-   [Terms](https://docs.github.com/site-policy/github-terms/github-terms-of-service)\n-   [Privacy](https://docs.github.com/site-policy/privacy-policies/github-privacy-statement)\n-   [Security](https://github.com/security)\n-   [Status](https://www.githubstatus.com/)\n-   [Community](https://github.community/)\n-   [Docs](https://docs.github.com/)\n-   [Contact](https://support.github.com?tags=dotcom-footer)\n-   Manage cookies\n-   Do not share my personal information